5|$|All {{undergraduates}} pursuing bachelor's {{degrees at}} Fordham {{are required to}} complete the <b>Core</b> <b>Curriculum,</b> a distribution of 17 courses in nine disciplines: English, mathematical/computational reasoning, social science, philosophy and ethics, history, fine arts, religious studies, natural science, and modern or Classical languages. Based on the curriculum established by the Society of Jesus in the sixteenth century, the Core is shared by Jesuit schools {{all over the world}} and emphasizes the liberal arts as a basis of education.|$|E
5|$|Founded in 1917, {{the college}} offers 49 majors and 34 minors and, {{beginning}} with the class of 2016, requires all its students to complete 16 credits in the Development of Western Civilization, {{which serves as a}} major part of the college's <b>core</b> <b>curriculum</b> (down from 20 credits previously). Fr. Brian Shanley has been the school's president since 2005.|$|E
5|$|In 1999, then-President Hugo Sonnenschein {{announced}} plans to relax the university's famed <b>core</b> <b>curriculum,</b> {{reducing the number of}} required courses from 21 to 15. When The New York Times, The Economist, and other major news outlets picked up this story, the university became the focal point of a national debate on education. The changes were ultimately implemented, but the controversy played a role in Sonnenschein's decision to resign in 2000.|$|E
